ce:section.ce:para:
In recent years, CDs have attracted significant attention as bactericidal agents that do not rely on antibiotics. In particular, the low or minimal toxicity, photostability, the potential for surface functionalization to enhance bacterial interactions, and the availability at low cost and harmless precursors that facilitate cost-effective and safe synthesis act as key qualities of CDs over other antibacterial substances (Dong et al., 2020). The excellent antibacterial potential of ICDs as recorded and compared with commercial antibiotic Streptomycin (Positive control) through the agar well diffusion method, indicates that it is highly effective against both gram positive (S. aureus and S. mutans) and gram negative (P. aeruginosa and E. coli) bacterial strains (Fig. 5
                     ) as evidenced by significant (P < 0.05) variation in inhibitory zones. Amongst, the gram-negative bacterial strains, E. coli was found to be more susceptible; wherein ICDs exhibited minimum inhibitory zone of 11 mm at lower (50 μg) and maximum of 13 mm at higher (50 μg) concentrations, respectively. On the same instance, the results on antibacterial activity of ICDs against gram-positive bacterial strains viz. S. aureus (10 and 11 mm) and S. mutans (11 and 12 mm) showed a marginal reduction in growth inhibitory zones at 50 μg and 100 μg compared to the gram-negative bacterial strains. In line with the results of our study, Varghese and Balachandran (2021) and Wu et al. (2019) have also substantiated the efficiency of CDs in rendering antagonistic activity against the bacterial pathogens. Several authors have reported that the antibacterial mechanism exhibited by CDs is most complex and distinct process as compared to conventional antibiotics. The underlying mechanism involves generation of reactive oxygen species, degradation of cell structure, and cytoplasmic leakage which occurs due to DNA binding and modulation of gene expression (Dong et al., 2020; Liang et al., 2021). The positive streptomycin recorded comparatively lesser inhibitory zones than ICDs against the test bacterial pathogens and thus highlights the noteworthy antibacterial potentials of ICDs. Table 1
                      clearly shows that this method offers superior levels of accuracy compared to alternative approaches.
